	"nodes":[
		{"id":"906ad0294af22fc0","x":-460,"y":-300,"width":780,"height":740,"type":"text","text":"### CAP Theorem: The Distributed Systems Trade-off\n\nThe **CAP Theorem** states that a distributed system can only provide **two out of three** of the following guarantees at the same time:\n\n---\n\n- **C - Consistency:** Every read receives the most recent write or an error. (Everyone sees the same data at the same time).\n    \n- **A - Availability:** Every request receives a (non-error) response, without the guarantee that it contains the most recent write. (The system is always up).\n    \n- **P - Partition Tolerance:** The system continues to operate despite an arbitrary number of messages being dropped (or delayed) by the network between nodes.\n    \n\n---\n\n### The \"Pick Two\" Combinations\n\n|**Combination**|**Description**|**Common Examples**|\n|---|---|---|\n|**CP** (Consistency + Partition Tolerance)|Keeps data correct but will \"shut down\" or error out if nodes can't talk.|**MongoDB, Redis, HBase**|\n|**AP** (Availability + Partition Tolerance)|Stays online during network issues but might show old/stale data.|**Cassandra, CouchDB, DynamoDB**|\n|**CA** (Consistency + Availability)|_Theoretically_ perfect, but impossible in distributed systems because network failures (**P**) are inevitable.|**Traditional RDBMS** (Single node)|"}
